{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658872"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:58:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20835"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20835"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97045"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13710"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20835"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79661"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"11598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12660"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33012"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97045"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMesenchymal tissues give rise to various types of benign and malignant neoplasms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a malignant neoplasm of mesenchymal origin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Osteoma","Giant cell tumour","Osteosarcoma","Enchondroma","Osteochondroma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a primary malignant bone tumour characterised by the production of osteoid matrix by neoplastic cells. It typically affects adolescents and young adults, with a predilection for the metaphyseal regions of long bones, particularly around the knee (distal femur and proximal tibia). The classic radiographic appearance includes a destructive lesion with periosteal reaction, often described as having a \u0027sunburst\u0027 or \u0027Codman\u0027s triangle\u0027 appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options represent benign bone tumours:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteochondroma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign cartilage-capped bony projection arising from the external surface of bone. It is the most common benign bone tumour and typically presents during skeletal growth.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign bone-forming tumour composed of well-differentiated mature bone. These are commonly found in the skull and facial bones.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiant cell tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign but locally aggressive neoplasm that typically affects the epiphyseal region of long bones in skeletally mature individuals. While generally benign, it can occasionally undergo malignant transformation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnchondroma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign cartilaginous tumour that develops within the medullary cavity of bone, most commonly in the small bones of the hands and feet.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther examples of malignant mesenchymal neoplasms (sarcomas) include liposarcoma (adipose tissue), rhabdomyosarcoma (skeletal muscle), leiomyosarcoma (smooth muscle), and chondrosarcoma (cartilage).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sarcomas are malignant neoplasms that arise from mesenchymal tissues such as bone, cartilage, fat, muscle, blood vessels, and connective tissue.","Osteosarcoma is a malignant bone tumour that typically affects adolescents and young adults.","Liposarcoma is a malignant tumour of adipose tissue, while rhabdomyosarcoma arises from skeletal muscle precursors.","Chondrosarcoma is a malignant cartilaginous tumour, and leiomyosarcoma arises from smooth muscle."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; 269."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79661"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20835"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79661"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T06:48:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T06:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13710"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97045"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11598"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Nomenclature","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12660","links":{